We factorise the equation: $(x-y)(x+y)=17$


If both $x$ and $y$ are positive, i.e., $x$ and $y$ are co-prime and one of them is divisible by $17$, we have the cases as $(x,y)=(17,0),(13,1),(5,12),(1,4)$. {{Ad hoc or the symmetric case}}


If both $x$ and $y$ are positive, for $(x+y-1)(x-y-1)=17-1=16$, we have $16=-16\cdot 1,-1\cdot-16,\ 8\cdot 2$ and $2\cdot8 $. {{Ad hoc or the symmetric case}}



The total number of solutions is $8$. <answer answer="8}}</answer>

