{eq}\left\{\begin{matrix} 2x+y=4\\ x+y=1 \\ x=0 \implies y=1\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\, LHS_{10};\,\,\, \left\{\begin{matrix} 2x+y=4\\ x+y=0\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\, RSH_{11};\,\,\,\,\,\, \left\{\begin{matrix} x+y=1 \\ x+y=0 \end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\, LHS_{20};\,\,\, \left\{\begin{matrix} x+y=1 \\ x=0\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\, RSH_2
{/eq}

{eq}\left\{\begin{matrix} 2x+y=4&\\ x=0&\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\,{\large current}:  \vec{V_1}=(0,4); \,\,\, \\{/eq}

{eq}\left\{\begin{matrix} 2x+y=4\\ x+y=1\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\, LHS_{11};\,\,\,\,\,\, \left\{\begin{matrix} x+y=1\\ x+y=0 \end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\, RSH_{12};\,\,\,\,\,\, \left\{\begin{matrix} x+y=1 \\ x=0\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\, RSH_3;\\
\\
\left\{\begin{matrix} x+y=1\\ x=0\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\,{\large current}:  \vec{V_2}=(0,1);
{/eq}

{eq}\left\{\begin{matrix} 2x+y=4&\\ x+y=0\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\,\,{\Large current}:  \vec{V_3}=([:- \infty _c, :+ \infty _ c]) \implies \vec{V_3}=\left\{2; 2\right\}\,\,\,\,\, \numalign{ interests the type of the boundary line}\\
\\
\left\{\begin{matrix} x+y=0&\\ x+y=1\end{matrix}\right. \,\,\,\,\,{\large current}:  \vec{V_4}=(1,0)\\
\\
\left\{\begin{matrix} x+y=1&\\ x=0\end{matrix}\right. =\vec{V_1}
{/eq}



Using the coordinates of the 4 vertices, we can compute the long sides of the quadrilateral:


